Benchmarks and stress tests:
  Framing: the reconciler IS `react-reconciler` (same Fiber engine as web React), so split
  results into (a) apples-to-apples reconcile work ‚Äî run the SAME component tree through a
  react-dom host and the Bevy host, the delta is pure host/bridge overhead ‚Äî and (b)
  apples-to-oranges paint (bevy_ui/GPU vs DOM). The headline artifact is a "reconciler is
  identical, here's the host overhead" chart.
  Library-specific:
    ‚òê Op-flush hot path (criterion, headless): `serde_v8` deserialize + `apply_js_ops`
      (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs`) + `ui_map` vs `Vec<Op>` length (10 ‚Üí 100k). Proves
      the "no JSON strings on the hot path" claim.
    ‚òê Mount cost vs tree shape: deep (10k-deep) vs wide (10k siblings) vs balanced.
    ‚òê Update amplification: change one prop deep in an N-node tree ‚Üí assert O(1) ops, not
      O(N). Guards against reconciler/`Op::Update` regressions (relates to the full-`Node`
      rebuild debt above).
    ‚òê Keyed-list churn: swap / insert / remove / reorder at scale.
    ‚òê End-to-end event round-trip latency (p50/p99 under load): click ‚Üí `uiEvent` ‚Üí
      handler ‚Üí setState ‚Üí flush ‚Üí applied. Extend `crates/core/tests/roundtrip.rs` with
      timing. Expect ~1 frame (Bevy‚ÜíJS is async via tokio mpsc ‚Üí `op_next_event`).
    ‚òê Bevy‚ÜíReact event flood / backpressure: produce events faster than React commits;
      watch the channel grow (ties to the unbounded-channels debt above).
    ‚òê Request/response under concurrency: many in-flight `op_request` correlations; verify
      none hang on malformed payloads.
    ‚òê Frame-budget interaction (HIGHEST VALUE FIRST): `op_flush` is sync on the Bevy main
      thread and shares the 16.6ms budget with the 3D sim. Measure dropped frames under a
      large flush. Specifically: do world-anchored elements (declared once by React,
      positioned every frame by a Bevy system ‚Äî NO per-frame bridge traffic) trigger a
      bevy_ui RELAYOUT on position change, or just transform/extract? If transform-only, N
      anchored badges scale almost free; if relayout, that's the cost to fix.
    ‚òê Animations engine: N concurrent animations/frame ‚Äî confirm values are driven
      Rust-side, not round-tripped to JS each frame.
    ‚òê Canvas rasterizer: `DrawCmd` throughput/frame.
    ‚òê Hot-reload latency + steady-state memory across many reloads (isolate stays alive).
    ‚òê Leak/steady-state: frame-time stability; entity count across repeated `selectScene`
      switches (verify `DespawnOnExit` reclaims).
  Cross-framework comparison (port to bevy-react + a vanilla react-dom impl):
    ‚òê js-framework-benchmark (krausest) operation set ‚Äî the industry-standard table:
      create 1k/10k rows, update every 10th, swap, select, remove, clear, append.
    ‚òê uibench (localvoid/uibench) ‚Äî clean reconciler-only comparison, minimal paint.
    ‚òê DBMonster / Sierpinski ‚Äî sustained high-frequency / deep-recursive update cases.
  Expectation (to validate): reconcile ‚âà web & faster than RN (Hermes); commit boundary
  faster than DOM mutation, ‚âà RN Fabric; layout slower than Blink at high node counts
  (the main risk); world-anchored UI AHEAD of web (web needs per-frame rAF + style writes,
  we do it in Rust/GPU with zero JS).